SLEEP / / Did you know sleeping on your left side when pregnant is recommended for blood flow and circulation, which can help you to sleep? It also means your heavy uterus won't put pressure on your liver, and helps the baby to receive the right amount of nutrients and oxygen through the placenta. It takes some practice, but even laying on your left side whenever you can will help. ✔️

.
via @stylish_bump 📷 @mayyabor

node.text:
12 hours before the twins were born ➡️ 12 months postpartum⁠
⁠
If I'm being quite honest, a year ago I pictured this transformation being a lot different. As a 22-year-old (at the time) I never pictured my first wrinkles would be between my bra line and my jeans. I didn't know tummy wrinkles were even a thing until they were a thing.⁠
⁠
I remember earlier in my pregnancy being concerned about what my C-section scar would look like. I remember at 30W pregnant when I cried when I noticed my first stretch mark.⁠
⁠
Then, I had the babies, and postpartum shocked me. I began to wonder when I would start to not look pregnant anymore, when my linea nigra would fade away, whether I could rid my stomach of wrinkles and stretch marks by rubbing creams and oil on it...⁠
⁠
People would tell me I looked great, and I would deflect their comments. I would even make fun of my body to AJ as a way of coping.⁠
⁠
I share all this to say that if I could go back and talk to my very pregnant 22-year-old self, I would tell myself to skip all of the crying, worrying, and criticism and start the process of realizing that stretch marks, scars, and loose skin don't define me. I would tell myself that I never needed to worry about "getting my body back" because I never lost it to begin with. This body has diligently been here for me the WHOLE time.⁠
⁠
The idea that you "lose" your body after you have a baby and that you need to "get your body back" post babies is a social myth that needs to be debunked. In fact, this body has done more amazing things for me in the past 12 months postpartum + 9 months of pregnancy before that than it EVER has before. From growing and delivering two full-size babies, to then feeding and nourishing those babies for over a year. I am immensely thankful for every way this body has shown up for me in the past 21 months.⁠
⁠
So, to my 22-year-old pregnant self, and to anyone that may need to hear this, show yourself love, patience, and gratitude. Your body has shown up for you, now it's time for you to show up for it. 💗⁠

.
⁠
📷 & words: @mrskatiecarlson

node.text:
WHEN DID GIVING BIRTH BECOME A COMPETITION?
. 
🔆 Your birth experience will become a blue print in your souls for the rest of your life.
.

❤️ If you are pregnant, check out the antenatal-hypnobirthing online course in bio ☺️ for an informed and better birth experience 🤩!
.

♥️ The way that you give birth doesn’t define you as a mother, as a women. 💪🏽Doesn’t represent how brave you are, how strong you are, because you already proved all that by bringing life into this world 👏🏻.
.
🔆 There is not an unique perfect birth for all of us.
.

♥️ There is no need to justify if birth didn’t go the way you thought, the way that others expected it to be.
.
♥️ A positive birth experience is not always related to the way you gave birth, it’s related to how in control of your own decisions you were, how you felt and how they made you feel.
.
♥️ Home birth 🏡, hospital birth 🏨, Caesarean birth 👩🏾‍⚕️, free birth, 💊medicated birth, unmediated birth 🙌🏽, unassisted and assisted birth.., every woman has her own reward.. her baby. . .
⭐️ Birth is not a battle where you have to prove anything, you already proved that you are able to create a miracle.
⭐️ Someone is not more mother by giving birth vaginally than via Caesarean section.
💙 Someone is not stronger who had a pain free labour than someone who didn’t.
💛 You are not a better mother if you had an unmediated birth than if you asked for extra help and you avoided to have a horrible experience about birth.
.
♥️ Birth doesn’t need to be labelled, birth and every single mom needs to be empowered, informed 📚 and respected ✊🏻✊🏾of her own decisions regarding her own birth.
.
❤️What kind of birth would you like to have? 
⁉️ What kind of birth did you had?👇🏻

Follow us @pregnancystyle_ 
.
.
.
.

Repost from @bumptobabyacademy
